{
  "answer": "Manusmriti chapter 12 (work slug: unknown-manusmrti-347b76, chapter 12, paragraph p-074f6e) gives an extended treatment of how the soul's three qualities—sattva, rajas, and tamas—govern the cycle of rebirth:\n\n**Definition of the three gunas (Mn_12.24–29):**\n- The three gunas are described as qualities of the Self by which the 'Great One' pervades all beings (12.24). Whichever guna predominates in the body at any time makes the embodied being predominantly of that guna (12.25).\n- Sattva = knowledge; tamas = ignorance; rajas = passion and aversion (12.26).\n- Sattva is what is joined with pleasure, tranquil and pure-seeming (12.27).\n- Rajas is joined with pain, repellent, and constantly captivates embodied beings (12.28).\n- Tamas is joined with delusion, unmanifest, of the nature of sense-objects, unknowable (12.29).\n\n**Characteristics of each guna (Mn_12.31–38):**\n- Sattva: study of the Veda, tapas, knowledge, purity, control of the senses, performance of Dharma, contemplation of the Self (12.31).\n- Rajas: taste for action, impatience, improper acts, constant indulgence in sense-objects (12.32).\n- Tamas: greed, sleep, lack of fortitude, cruelty, atheism, dissolute life, begging, carelessness (12.33).\n- Summary: the characteristic of tamas is desire; of rajas, worldly gain; of sattva, Dharma—excellence in ascending order (12.38).\n\n**Rebirth outcomes determined by gunas (Mn_12.40–50):**\n- Those predominantly sattva go to the state of gods.\n- Those predominantly rajas go to the state of men.\n- Those predominantly tamas go to the state of beasts.\nThis threefold result is further subdivided into low, middle, and high grades within each guna (Mn_12.41–50):\n- Tamas (low): immovable things, worms, insects, fish, snakes, tortoises, cattle, wild animals.\n- Tamas (middle): elephants, horses, Shudras, Mlecchas, lions, tigers, boars.\n- Tamas (high): Caranas, Suparnas, hypocritical men, Rakshasas, Pisachas.\n- Rajas (low): acrobats, actors, men living by the sword, gamblers, drunkards.\n- Rajas (middle): kings and Kshatriyas, family priests of kings, those who delight in battles.\n- Rajas (high): Gandharvas, Yakshas, attendants of the gods, apsaras.\n- Sattva (first): ascetics, mendicants, Brahmanas, celestial beings, constellations, Daityas.\n- Sattva (second): sacrificers, sages, gods, the Vedas, heavenly lights, years, ancestors, sadhyas.\n- Sattva (highest): Brahma, creators of the world, Dharma, the Great One, and the Unmanifest.\n\nThe chapter concludes this section by stating that this entire threefold cycle of rebirth has been declared for the three kinds of action (12.51).",
